review_text:
Every year for my 'Satogaeri' trip to Japan, we have travelled to and from Narita, but this year we have decided to travel back to the UK via Haneda using JAL just on the inbound flight ( our outbound flight was by Finnair). Before this I flew with JAL before but operated by Finnair or BA ( I think), and didn't get a good trip. This time I flew back from Haneda to London Heathrow with JAL operated airline. My honest opinion was that on the whole I did enjoy the trip back to the UK this time and the services ( ranging from airline food, in-flight entertainment system and so on) were good. 
(1) Legrooms: the most important of all for me was the legroom on the Economy seat, as everything depended on it for the duration of 12 hour flight, which would be bound to cause extra strain on myself as I age on all annual trips ! To my relief, JAL operated fleet does provide a good and wide enough legroom for Economy class seats, so I was very pleased with it. Even with the reclined seat by the person in front of me ( this time again ) I still had enough leg room to stretch my legs, which was good, but the only snag was the reclined seat got me a shorter distance between the flight entertainment screen and my eyes and I had to keep my head away from the screen to give me the right distance for correct angles and viewing ( the tilting of the screen didn't help me in this case);
(2) flight meals: I think JAL were quite generous in providing more than sufficient amount of meals to passengers on this flight ( JL43). I think I have an average appetite just like other people, but the long haul flight can influence my appetite quite easily too. On this flight, I did enjoy the meal that was served first after the takeoff from Haneda. The choice of meal was adequate, it was either beef or chicken dish with rice and I chose the latter and enjoyed it.But it was quite a heavy meal with good amount of rice and chocolate mousse as a desert. We were also provided with a small pot of Hagen Daz ice cream after that. The  meal was served really quickly and all the food with trays were removed swiftly afterwards. Then about half way through the flight journey we were woken up again by serving of another light meal,which proved to be quite heavy for my stomach. It was a oval shaped bun with tuna mayo filling. I love tuna mayo, but my stomach was still digesting the previous meal when this was served 6 hours later. But being a glutton for food I couldn't refuse, so I consumed it, which turned out to be a bad mistake. Then about 2 hours before the landing we were served for the final time another supper. My stomach was still full with previous two course meals in it, but I couldn't say no to this meal either, as JAL was serving 吉野家の牛丼, which I never had before as a flight meal. I don't know what non- Japanese passengers thought of this last meal, but I was quite intrigued by this meal as this company, Yoshinoya was ubiquitously known in Japan like MacDonalds in early 80's ( I think) selling their best selling product, Beef bowl with rice ( Gyudon) and I never had a chance to eat any of their product until this flight. Timing was unfortuante though as my palate was somewhat paralysed with full stomach, which struggled to operate and I could just taste the beef and egg sauce. All I remember in this flight was feeling queasy and full stomach;
(3) Air circulation and temperature within the aircraft:
The only thing I would seriously complain in this trip was about this matter. I noticed quite a number of passengers were sneezing several times and I found the temperature in the aircraft really hot. In fact, for the whole journey I was feeling really hot and regretted I should have come in with short sleeved shirt.  I wonder if I was one of the few passengers who experienced hot air during the whole journey;
(4) in-flight entertainmment system:
The selection of entertainment was adequate for me. I would normally read a book or listen to my own personal audio player anyway, so I didn't miss much even if there weren't enough choice in the flight system. But I think the improvement was made for the touch screen system. I wasn't keen on this screen when it was first introduced because if you had a passenger behind you who would use the touch screen in ' Rocky' manner, he/she would simply punch the screen to select/ deselect each time and I would be the victim of being punched at the back for the whole 12 hour journey. That would be my nightmare. It did happen to me once with codeshare flight. However on this journey, I only felt some light tap a few times from behind and hardly noticed it most of the time. Or maybe I was lucky to be seated with a very considerate passenger behind me. 
Overall this trip from Haneda to London Heathrow was good and pleasant despite the lack of sleep ( as I always experience on every long haul flight). The only other comment I would make is about the seating plan. In this flight, the fleet had a seating plan of 3 ( left) - 3( centre) -3 ( right) seats in most rows in Economy class. At the check-in counter we both wanted aisle seats and we were told that we would get aisle seats as there were two seats, but when we got into the aircraft we realised we were allocated one aisle and the seat next to it ( middle seat). We didn't minds getting two aisle seats with front and back, and I think the JAL staff who served us possibly misunderstood us. 
But we relatively had a good and almost problem free flight on this trip, so we would certainly consider JAL to be one of the possible candidate flight carrier for our journey next year.  We have used Finnair for the past few years  and their service has been equally good too, but with the Brexit situation in the UK yet to be settled we  would have to find out what each airline could offer next year.
